User story As a developer, when I configure backend services, I want to ensure that HikariCP connection pool settings are explicit so that they use the intended conservative settings. As a system administrator, when I deploy services, I want to verify that the idle connection count is within acceptable limits so that resource usage is optimized. Context Three backend services are currently using default HikariCP connection pool settings. This leads to excessive idle database connections, which is not aligned with the conservative settings used by other services in the codebase. Acceptance criteria All three services have explicit HikariCP pool configuration in their application.yml files. Default environment variables are added to the relevant Docker Compose environment files. The idle connection count is verified in at least one environment after deployment. Other information Affected services: ams/backend/app-services/src/main/resources/application.yml ams/backend/pad-services/src/main/resources/application.yml rules/backend/service/src/main/resources/application.yml Proposed configuration to add: spring:
  datasource:
    hikari:
      minimum-idle: ${_DB_MIN_IDLE:1}
      maximum-pool-size: ${_DB_MAX_POOL:3}
      connection-timeout: ${_DB_CONN_TIMEOUT:3000} Additional action: Audit deployed environment variable values for services with Hikari configuration to ensure they match the repo defaults (1/3/3000) and are not overridden at the deployment layer.

