BLGW class  AbstractKafkaConsumerService  was converted to a  streams  API a while back. Before that it used to explicitly emit DataRow into the Flux. The stream is built purely from Kafka using Flux.replay().autoConnect() with no injection point. Add Injection Sink Add a  Sinks.Many<DataRow>  to AbstractKafkaConsumerService and merge it with the Kafka stream: ┌─────────────┐     ┌──────────────────────┐
  │   Kafka     │────>│  Kafka Stream        │──────┐
  │   Topics    │     │  (replay/autoConnect)│      │
  └─────────────┘     └──────────────────────┘      │
                                                    ├──> Flux.merge() ──> sharedStream
  ┌─────────────┐     ┌──────────────────────┐      │
  │  External   │────>│  Injection Sink      │──────┘
  │  DataRows   │     │  (Sinks.Many)        │
  └─────────────┘     └──────────────────────┘ AbstractKafkaConsumerService.java : 1.  Add injection sink field: private volatile Sinks.Many<DataRow> injectionSink; 2.  Modify  initializeSharedStreamUnsafe()  to: Create the injection sink: Sinks.many().multicast().onBackpressureBuffer() Merge the injection sink's flux with the Kafka stream before applying heartbeats 3. Implement  emitDataRowToStream() : public void emitDataRowToStream(DataRow dataRow) {
     if (injectionSink != null) {
         injectionSink.emitNext(dataRow, Sinks.EmitFailureHandler.FAIL_FAST);
     } else {
         logger.warn("Cannot emit DataRow - stream not initialized");
     }
 }

